On Mon, Jul 6, 2009 at 11:00 AM, Mike Soultanian <msoultan(-at-)csulb.edu> wrote:

> Pratt, Bob, VBABOST wrote:
>
>> going to the front of the vehicle were shredded at the ends and look like
>> they are frozen in place. Are there any articles on how to replace these
>> and
>> a source for same.
>>
>
> Not that I know of, but they aren't that hard to change, assuming the
> sheath isn't frozen in the steel guide tubes.  You just purchase new cables
> and then feed them through from the front to the back.
>
> Now, my cables were frozen in the tubes so I had to cut out the steel guide
> tubes and then I ran copper guide tubes zip-tied in place of the steel tubes
> - I cut the tubing into sections to make it more workable and then used some
> clear tubing at the breaks and then used zip-ties to seal those junctions.
>  The tubes only purpose is to guide the cable to the back, so it worked out
> great.  It was just a tedious process...
>
> While you're under there, you might as well redo all the heater ducting.  I
> ran new ducting wrapped with the aluminum bubble wrap and the heat comes out
> hotter than you can hold your hand over.
>
> Mike
